More often than not, employees of High Kill shelters started working there to make a difference. They wanted to help the animals and the communities they serve. However, the true blame falls on the sheer number of animals being relinquished and brought into the shelters. State & Federally funded shelters must intake all animals brought to the shelter. This means, if there is no cage space, the longest resident, or sickest, or labeled aggressive will likely need to be euthanized first to make room for the constant flow. More pet owners need to spay & neuter their pets. More pet owners need to adopt responsibly with the understanding they are making a 15 year + commitment to the animal. More programs need to be created to promote TNR (Trap-Neuter-Return) of feral community cats, and more Education & Awareness needs to be made to the general public. We can all make a difference by helping educate others, getting our pets fixed & microchipped, and TNRing local cats so they dont continue to reproduce. We need more adopters to ADOPT instead of buying from breeders. Instead of blaming the shelters and their workers...lets work together to help our local communities.

Declawing is NEVER okay! Barring any major medical reason for a declaw (which is RARE), there is absolutely no reason you should ever declaw your pet. Declawing is the process of surgically amputating each toe up to the first knuckle. Declawed cats often exhibit pain for the rest of their life, later arthritis, regrowth of some bones causing a need for additional surgeries, litter issues, biting issues, inability to defend ones' self, and major behavioral problems. Instead, provide your cat with appropriate places to scratch (tall scratching posts taller than the length of their body so they can stretch), add protections to your furniture if needed, use 'soft paw' nail caps, trim your cats nails regularly (or have a groomer do them), or just...don't own a cat. Cats are meant to scratch. Its a behavioral necessity for health and well-being. Let your kitties keep their claws <3

It is not inhumane to keep a cat indoor-only. Cats are exposed to a variety of dangers, parasites, and diseases when allowed outdoors. Some hazards include: Fleas, Worms, Giardia, Coccidia, FIV, FeLV, Coyotes, Other Wildlife including cats & dogs, unkind humans, cars, and more. Cats can be incredibly happy living an indoor only life, especially if you provide them with plenty of enrichment. Create perches by the window ledges, use lots of toys, and provide 'hunt' type activities like the laser pointer! This will help ensure your kitty remains happy and healthy.
If you'd like to provide a safe outdoor space for your cat, consider an enclosed catio! Another great option for cats interested in exploring the outdoors; training them on a leash & harness! Always keep your kitty safe and either keep the indoors, or monitor their outdoor time. Do not leave them unattended to roam the streets.

We hear this often in rescue! 'I want a russian blue because I heard they were hypoallergenic and I have allergies.' There is NO such thing as a 100% hypoallergenic cat or dog AND it is not breed specific. Some breeds have been 'known' for being hypoallergenic but this is completely a falsehood. Cats & dogs CAN be low dander but a genetic test would need to be performed on the pet to confirm. Low dander animals can and will still produce an allergic response, just not as strong. Also, the belief that specific breed will always be low dander is also false. More often than not, people buy purebreds from breeders due to allergies and end up still highly allergic to their pet. This causes the animal to either be returned or dumped in the shelters. Our suggestion is to spend time with the animal you are adopting beforehand, not adopt a 'specific breed' as it means nothing in terms of allergens, take some allergy meds/allergy shots, and bathe your pet to reduce the dander on their fur (which is caused by saliva).

Hi guys! For those wondering about the Harbor City Warehouse hoarder case we posted about a few weeks ago...all kitties have left the warehouse! Big shout out to all the different rescues coming together in a collaborative effort to save these cats! There are still about 23 needing placement currently in temporary foster care (however in cages so we'd love placement for them ASAP). If you know of any rescues willing to help one or two, let us know! Or if you live in Southern California and willing to foster, please email FFLRescueNetwork@gmail.com We will be able to direct you to fellow rescues looking for fosters. Please only commit to foster if you're 100% committed to do so. Friends for Life Rescue Network has rescued 5 of the kitties from this location with a number of illnesses. The bills are starting to wrack up pretty high! ***Please consider a donation of any amount to Paypal.me/FFLRescueNetwork so we can then rescue more once these guys are healthy and adoptable!***

Hi all! We have some STUNNING kittens up for adoption in Southern California! Local residents only please.

1- Hermione- Female- Bonded Pair with Squeaker (#8). Bottle fed since she was a day old. She starts purring if you just look at her. She's constantly in a state of perpetual purrs! She loves to snuggle, pounce on your legs as you walk by (gently) and knead on her favorite blanket!
2- Harry Pawter- Female- Bottle fed since day 1. Super affectionate and wants to be with you always. Loves to be held and cries for attention.

3- Joker- Male- Exceedingly affectionate. He's a tiny boy who follows you around like a puppy

4- Harper- Female- Found in a box. Super playful, loving, and very neat!

5. Riddler- Male- Cuddle monkey who needs to snuggle with you every night

6. Sirius- Male- Incredibly sweet and loves to play with everyone.

7- Snape- Male- NEEDY. Screams for you to hold him, needs to be snuggled all the time, and must be the center of your work.

8- Squeaker- Male- Bonded with Hermione. He loves eskimo kisses, snuggles, and playing with Hermione.
9- Lee- Male- Super sweet and hops around like a bunny when playing!

10- Lex Luthor- Male- Incredibly social and loves to greet people at the door! He's playful and gets along with everyone. Enjoys being held.

@FFLRescueNetwork "Hiiiii! My name is Doby! I am an amazing cleft nose kitten in the rescue who also has Cerebellar Hyperplasia. They all say I'm purrfect! Do you think so too?" Because Doby has a cleft nose and not a cleft palate, it does not effect his ability to eat or breathe. He breathes similar to a smooshy faced kitty. Cerebellar Hyperplasia is a non progressive disorder that causes kitties to shake. It does not ever get worse and ranges from mild to severe. CH kitties tends to live normal lives and function well with eating, playing, and litterbox use.
There are a few CH kitties available in southern California. We would be happy to put you in touch with those rescues. Send us a DM for more information!

"Hi! My name is Juniper and I'm FIV +. I'd love to share some FIV facts with you!" What is FIV?
"FIV is an autoimmune disorder. Cats that have FIV often can't fight off infections as easily as non FIV cats. A healthy diet, vitamins, and an annual vet check up should keep me in tip top shape!" How long does a cat with FIV live?
"FIV cats generally live a normal, long, happy life." Do FIV cats need medicine?
"They do not need regular medication. Vitamins and nutrients can help keep our immune system strong as does keeping us indoors." Can people get FIV?
"Not at all! Its strictly a feline species specific disorder." How does a cat get FIV?
"Blood, bite, mating, or birth. Transmission of FIV from one cat to another is very low and highly unlikely unless they are fighting. Transmission is most common in colonies of unneutered fighting males. We can live peacefully with FIV negative cats with no risk of transmission!

My mama, Eira, and I are both up for adoption! Email FFLRescueNetwork@gmail.com to inquire. We hope this post was informative and that you'd consider adopting and FIV kitty." @FFLRescueNetwork
